\title{Coiled-Spring Prong Electrodes}
\author{monaduck1069}
\import{macros}
\date{2026-03-31}
\taxon{reference}
\tag{electrode}
\tag{comfort}
\tag{3d-print}

\p{Spring-loaded prongs provide compliant contact that absorbs micro-movements during extended sessions. Each prong independently adjusts to scalp curvature, maintaining consistent impedance without the rigid pressure points of fixed pins.}

\subtree{
\title{Design}

\p{A 3D-printed PLA or ABS holder houses 6-8 cylindrical pockets. Each pocket contains a stainless steel compression spring (6mm length, 3mm diameter) topped with a conductive contact tip. The spring provides 0.1-0.3N of force per prong — enough for scalp contact through hair, gentle enough to avoid pain over hours.}

\p{Comfort advantage over rigid pins: when the rider moves or the cap shifts, springs absorb the displacement instead of digging in. Comfort advantage over arches: simpler geometry, no need for flexible filament.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Materials}

\ul{
  \li{\strong{Holder}: PLA or PETG, standard FDM. The holder is rigid; compliance comes from the springs.}
  \li{\strong{Springs}: Stainless steel compression springs. McMaster-Carr 9657K72 (5.56mm length, 3.18mm OD) or equivalent. ~$0.15/spring.}
  \li{\strong{Tips}: Gold-plated pogo pins (P75-B1, widely available), or silver-plated brass rivets.}
  \li{\strong{Total cost}: ~$2/electrode (holder: $0.10 filament, springs: $1.20 for 8, tips: $0.70).}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Comfort for Extended Sessions}

\p{Kimura et al. (Sensors, 2020, doi:10.3390/s20174733):}
\ul{
  \li{Validated alpha-band detection comparable to wet Ag/AgCl electrodes}
  \li{Spring force tunable by spring constant selection — softer springs for comfort, stiffer for thick hair}
  \li{No degradation of contact quality during 30+ minute recordings}
}

\p{Comfort tips for 2+ hour sessions:}
\ul{
  \li{Use lighter springs (0.1N) for temporal and frontal positions where scalp is thinner}
  \li{Use stiffer springs (0.3N) for occipital positions where hair is thickest}
  \li{Round all contact tips — no sharp edges. File or tumble-polish pogo pins before assembly.}
  \li{Add a thin silicone washer (1mm, Shore A 40) between holder base and cap fabric as a pressure buffer}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Source}
\p{Kimura, M., Nakatani, S., Nishida, S., Taketoshi, D., Araki, N. "3D Printable Dry EEG Electrodes with Coiled-Spring Prongs." \em{Sensors}, 20(17), 4733 (2020). GitHub: \code{https://github.com/1nakatan/EEG_electrodes_with_coiled-spring_prongs}}
}
